  only if you have no influence on the fund’s investment policy and
  the fund’s main purpose is not to invest in assets explicitly
  prohibited by the rules (see especially funds that mainly invest in
  individual marketable shares/bonds or related derivatives of
  financial corporations). Also avoid transactions with entities with
  whom you have an ongoing professional relationship on behalf of the
  ECB, observe the EUR 10 000 monthly thresholds, and do not split
  transactions to circumvent limits. Seek prior authorisation where
  required and report ex‑post where applicable.  With that in mind,
  the types of investment funds that are generally appropriate and
  most likely to comply with the Rules are: - Broad, diversified
  collective investment schemes (e.g., global or regional equity index
  funds or multi‑asset funds) where you have no influence on
  investment policy. These are unlikely to have “as their main
  purpose” investing in the prohibited category. - Passive, broad-
  market ETFs or mutual funds that track broad indices (global/World,
  MSCI ACWI, S&P 500, Euro Stoxx 50) — provided they are not sector-
  or issuer-concentrated. - Target‑date or lifecycle funds and
  diversified multi‑asset funds that spread risk across many issuers
  and sectors. - Diversified bond funds (investment-grade or aggregate
  bond funds) only if they are not concentrated in bonds issued
  predominantly by financial corporations (check portfolio
  composition). - Money-market funds or short-term liquidity funds for
  parking savings — but check concentration rules and thresholds. -
  Insurance products or annuities are explicitly listed as exempt
  transactions (purchase/redemption of insurance policies or
  annuities).  Avoid or treat with caution: - Funds whose stated main
  purpose is to invest primarily in financial‑sector equities or
  financial‑sector bonds (these would fall under the prohibited
  category). - Sector funds focused on banks/financials, single‑issuer
  or concentrated funds, private equity or hedge funds with heavy
  derivatives exposure, complex structured products, or funds that
  would require prior authorisation under the Rules without obtaining
  it. - Any transaction that involves an entity/individual with whom
  you have an ongoing professional relationship on behalf of the ECB.
  - Splitting transactions to stay under EUR 10 000 per month — this
  is disallowed.  Practical next steps: 1. Before investing, review
  the fund prospectus/strategy to confirm the fund’s main purpose and
  sector/issuer concentration. 2. Check whether the fund holds mainly
  financial‑corporation securities or uses derivatives in ways that
  would trigger restrictions. 3. Contact your compliance office (or
  follow the ECB’s internal procedures) for confirmation and to obtain
  any required prior authorisation or to arrange ex‑post reporting. 4.
  Keep records of transactions and ensure monthly totals (e.g.,
  foreign exchange or other transactions) do not breach the EUR 10 000
  threshold by splitting.  If you are not an ECB staff member, these
  specific rules do not apply; tell me whether you want general fund
  recommendations for a specific risk profile, time horizon and
  amount, and I can give more general investment options.
